{"title":"How much is the 2023 Vuelta a España prize money?","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-prize-money","date":1692967601000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-prize-money\">How much is the 2023 Vuelta a España prize money?</a></p>\n\n<p>This year the organisers of the Vuelta a España will dish out €1,118,205 (approx £958,310) in prize money. That’s just less than half the prize pot at the Tour de France and, like the Tour, most is allocated to the general classification, with the final red jersey earning the winner €150,000, with nearly €60,000 for second and €30,000 for third.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here’s how it’s divvied out. </p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-red-jersey\">The Vuelta a España leader’s red jersey: Everything you need to know</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-a-espana-favourites\">Who are the favourites for the 2023 Vuelta a España?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/how-watch-vuelta-espana\">How to watch and live stream the Vuelta a España 2023</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/vuelta-a-espana-route-race-reports-tv-guide-and-all-you-need-to-know\">Vuelta a España 2023: Stage-by-stage preview and everything we know so far</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>General classification</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-2048x1366.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Evenepoel-wins-2022-Vuelta-by-UnipublicCharly_Lopez-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Unipublic/Charly Lopez</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The most significant single chunk of prize money on offer will go to the overall winner, who’ll take home €150,000. This drops to €57,985 for second place, with the last step on the podium in Madrid getting a handy €30,000. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Behind them, the top ten are also relatively well remunerated. Interestingly, every rider between 10th and 20th in Madrid receives the same €3,800 lump sum. The leader of the general classification at the end of each stage also receives €500.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Prizes for the final general classification</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1st: </strong>€150,000<br /><strong>2nd:</strong> €57,985<br /><strong>3rd: </strong>€30,000<br /><strong>4th: </strong>€15,000<br /><strong>5th:</strong> €12,500<br /><strong>6th:</strong> €9,000<br /><strong>7th:</strong> €9,000<br /><strong>8th: </strong>€6,000<br /><strong>9th:</strong> €6,000<br /><strong>10th to 20th:</strong> €3,800</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Total:</strong> €337,285</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Individual stage wins</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Groenewegen-Vuelta-2022-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling.jpg 1417w\" /><figcaption>Luis Angel Gomez / SprintCycling</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Each stage winner will bank a handy €11,000 for their efforts. Prizes for placings on each stage are distributed all the way down to the 20th finisher, giving even those well behind the leader a reason to put on a show for the fans. Once added together over the race’s 21 stages, a total of €606,060 will be handed out.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Prizes for each stage</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1st: </strong>€11,000<br /><strong>2nd: </strong>€5,500<br /><strong>3rd: </strong>€2,700<br /><strong>4th: </strong>€1,500<br /><strong>5th: </strong>€1,100<br /><strong>6th:</strong> €900<br /><strong>7th:</strong> €900<br /><strong>8th:</strong> €650<br /><strong>9th:</strong> €650<br /><strong>10th to 20th:</strong> €360</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Total per stage:</strong> €28,860</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Points, mountains and young riders’ classifications</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Jersey-podium-2022-Vuelta-UnipublicCharly-Lopez-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Unipublic/Charly Lopez</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>While there are points to be won for taking sprints or mountain summits, the leaders of the mountains and points jerseys receive a daily reward for heading their particular classifications. While each red jersey is worth €500 each day, the leader in the points competition gets <em>only</em> €100 for each day they hold on to the green jersey.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The same goes for the leader of the mountains competition. The best young rider, meanwhile, gets just €70 a day, barely enough to keep them stocked up on sweets and fizzy pop in the current climate.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The rider that claims each of the jerseys at the end of the race however will do a bit better. The winner of the mountains competition does best of all with €13,000 while the best young rider and the points competition winner both pocket €11,000.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Young rider and Points classification overall</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1st:</strong> €11,000<br /><strong>2nd:</strong> €5,000<br /><strong>3rd:</strong> €2,000</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Mountains classification overall</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1st:</strong> €13,000<br /><strong>2nd:</strong> €6,600<br /><strong>3rd: </strong>€3,500</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Climbs and sprints</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>On the way to Madrid, there will be numerous intermediate sprints and categorised climbs. Each sprint will see the first three riders over the line awarded €550, €180, and €95 respectively.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For the climbers, there are four ‘ESP’ climbs (or special category, comparable to the HC <em>‘hors catégorie’ </em>classification at the Tour de France). First over gets €920 and second receives €615. First category climbs have €460 and €310 on offer to the leading riders, second category climbs offer €230 and €155, and third category €115 and €80. </p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Alberto Fernández mountain prize</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"798\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023-798x970.png\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023-798x970.png 798w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023-247x300.png 247w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023-768x934.png 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023-750x912.png 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Col-du-Tourmalet-Vuelta-2023.png 960w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Like the Souvenir Henri Desgrange awarded to the first riders over the highest peak at the Tour, the Vuelta celebrates the crossing of its highest point with a special prize. Named after an esteemed Spanish racer who died in a car crash in 1984, this year’s Alberto Fernández mountain prize will be awarded to the first rider over the Col du Tourmalet (18.9km, 7.4%) on Stage 13.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Reaching the summit first will net you €1,000, while the second rider will gain €520.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Teams classification</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-970x647.jpg\" alt srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling-350x233.jpg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/08/Soudal-QuickStep-at-2022-Vuelta-by-Luis-Angel-Gomez-SprintCycling.jpg 1417w\" /><figcaption>Luis Angel Gomez / SprintCycling</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The team classification for each stage is calculated by adding the times of the three leading riders from each squad. At the end of the day, the first place team on that stage gets €400, with the second placed squad receiving €200, while the third placed wins €100.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>At the end of the three weeks of racing, the team finishing first receives €12,500, with prize money awarded down to the eighth placed outfit.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Team classification overall</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>1st:</strong> €12,500<br /><strong>2nd: </strong>€7,500<br /><strong>3rd: </strong>€5,500<br /><strong>4th:</strong> €4,300<br /><strong>5th: </strong>€3,200<br /><strong>6th:</strong> €2,200<br /><strong>7th: </strong>€1,100<br /><strong>8th:</strong> €1,100</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Most aggressive rider</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The rider deemed most combative each day wins the gold number for the following day along with €200. The rider considered the most aggressive throughout the entire race wins €3,000.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Distribution of funds</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>While you might expect a successful racer to come away with a good amount of cash, by tradition, any money won throughout the race is put in a kitty and divided between riders and backroom staff. Cycling is<em> </em>a team sport after all.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>For more coverage on the Vuelta a España, visit our <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/vuelta-a-espana\" target=\"_blank\">hub page.</a></em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/vuelta-espana-prize-money\">How much is the 2023 Vuelta a España prize money?</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"jdelves","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"75468591bbebbf84047d9d68dcfaf4e66d270594b7a81ffa0ca7f750574c889d","category":"Cycling"}